@node WHAT_IS_IT "Introduction to fMSX"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Introduction to fMSX@{fg text}

@{jleft}

fMSX stands for @{U}@{B}F@{UB}ast @{B}MSX@{UB}@{UU}, and that's what it is: a reasonably speedy
emulation of the @{"MSX" link MSX} computer system.


fMSX Amiga is based on the original work of Marat Fayzullin (fms@komkon.org).
However, by now every single line of code has changed, and there is
absolutely no connection between fMSX UNIX and fMSX Amiga anymore.


fMSX Amiga has come a long way from its commandline roots. From the early
days, where you could see each sprite being painstakingly plotted, to the
current version with its full-featured GUI and support for every piece of
hardware imaginable, some 30,000 lines of code were written, and then
rewritten, sometimes many times. Nowadays fMSX Amiga is built from a mix
of assembly, C, and C++.


fMSX Amiga is a reasonably complete MSX emulator. It will run MSX ROMs
(including ROMs bigger than 32K, and including GameMaster), disk images, real
disks, MSX files that are not on a disk image, and tape images. Its
compatibility is fairly high, not just with MSX software but also with MSX
hardware: joysticks, mouse, numerous soundchips (PSG, SCC, SCC+, and FM-Pac),
Kanji ROMs and more are all supported.


In addition to all this fMSX Amiga also doubles as a Colecovision emulator.


In order to test the various fMSX versions I have selected a short BASIC
program as a benchmark. Don't take this too seriously: the timing results
obtained from running this problem are very different depending on the
settings of fMSX.

@{code}
    @{fg shine}10 FORT=1TO10000
    20 NEXTT@{fg text}

    @{U}Machine@{UU}               @{U}Time@{UU}
    a4000/30              94 seconds (fMSX 0.3, original version)
    Sun Sparc 2           86 seconds (fMSX 0.4, UNIX version)
    Sun Tatung            43 seconds (fMSX 0.4, UNIX version)
    a4000/30              22 seconds (fMSX 0.3, modified version)
    a4000/60              22 seconds (fMSX Amiga 2.0, with speed control)
    a4000/60              22 seconds (fMSX Amiga 2.1, with speed control)
    @{B}VG-8235 MSX2          21 seconds@{UB}
    a4000/40              15 seconds (fMSX Amiga 0.2, standard settings)
    a4000/40 (warp 4040)   9 seconds (fMSX 0.3, modified)
    a4000/60               7 seconds (fMSX Amiga 1.4)
    MSX Turbo-R/RAM mode   6 seconds
    @{B}a4000/60               5 seconds (fMSX Amiga 2.0, without speed control)@{UB}
    @{B}a4000/60               5 seconds (fMSX Amiga 2.1, without speed control)@{UB}
@{body}

The ideal speed here is the one tested on the VG-8235, which is a real MSX
machine. Since version 2.0, fMSX is available in two versions: one that always
runs at precisely MSX speed and one that always runs as fast as possible.


The MSX Turbo-R was the last MSX machine that ever came out. It was using an
R800 CPU, which is a Z80 variant that executes almost every instruction in a
single cycle. Due to this, and some added instructions, it reaches speeds
comparable to a Z80 running at 28MHz.

@endnode

