@node COPYRIGHTS "Copyright"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Copyright@{fg text}

@{jleft}

fMSX Amiga is publicly supported freeware. Its sources are available
on request from me, and you can modify them as long as you notify me about
modifications.


You can't use fMSX for commercial purposes though. If you want to market
anything based on fMSX source or executables, contact @{"me" link AUTHOR} please.@{fg text}


If your conscience does not allow you to work with software you did not
pay for, neither author refuses gifts, money or postcards. I'd appreciate
it very much if you were to send me email!

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node INSTALLATION "Installation"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Installation@{fg text}

@{jleft}

No specific installation procedure is required, just drag the directory
containing fMSX to some place of your liking. Note that the files "fmsx"
and "fmsx.data" absolutely have to be in the same directory!


Note: do not copy the @{fg shine}MSXFonts/@{fg text} directory to @{fg shine}FONTS:@{fg text}! The fonts in that
directory are in MSX format, not in Amiga format.


@{I}To run cartridge images from the Workbench:@{UI}


Many games come with pre-made icons. These icons require that @{fg shine}fMSX:@{fg text}
 is assigned to the directory where you installed fMSX.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node REQUIREMENTS "System requirements"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}System requirements@{fg text}

@{jleft}
@{lindent 4}

Required are:

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Amiga OS 3.0

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} 68020 processor

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} 3MB RAM


Recommended:

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} AHI (required for some soundmodes)

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} 68060 processor

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} A Concierto soundcard (for near-perfect FM-PAC emulation)
@{lindent 0}


If you want to use real MSX disks, you will need to have CrossDos or similar
installed. CrossDos has been part of the AmigaOS since v2.1. Shareware
alternatives are available on Aminet.


Since fMSX 2.0, fMSX allocates RAM dynamically (earlier versions used mainly
static allocations). It also uses a lot more RAM. However, fMSX can run on
native CyberGfx screens now, in which case it uses almost no CHIP RAM.
@{lindent 4}


This program was developed using:

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} An a4000/060/PPC with 64MB RAM, 2.2GB HD, Picasso IV + Concierto

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} SAS/C 6.57

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} GenAm 3.02

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} TurboText 2.0

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node LOADINGEMULATOR "Running the emulator"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Running the emulator@{fg text}

@{jleft}

@{B}From the shell@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Type @{fg shine}fMSX@{fg text} to start the program. It is possible to load a cartridge
file or disk by typing @{fg shine}fMSX <ROM-NAME>@{fg text}, which will load the
specified cartridge. A full pathname may be used when specifying the cartridge.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}From workbench@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Double click on the fMSX icon to start the emulator without loading any
cartridges.


Loading a cartridge is accomplished by double-clicking it. Note that
the included game icon requires the directory @{fg shine}fMSX:@{fg text} to be assigned
to the directory where the emulator resides. You will need the shell to
create this assign.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node CONTROLWINDOW "The control window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The control window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

This is the main window of fMSX Amiga. Closing it closes the entire program.
In it you can set the most important options.


@{B}Skipped frames@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This is the number of frames skipped before a new frame is drawn. If this
number has a low value the emulation runs smooth and slow. If it has a high
value it runs faster but also less smooth. Try to experiment with what works
best for your system.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Interrupt rate@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This controls the speed at which interrupts are generated. Normal MSX machines
run at either PAL (50 interrupts per second) or NTSC (60 interrupts per
second) speed, but fMSX Amiga also allows you to use a custom speed (from 10
to 100 interrupts per second), allowing you to run programs at exactly the
speed you desire.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Running / Paused / Music@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If you need every last cycle your machine can provide, but are unwilling to
quit fMSX because you just reached level 48 of Tetris, you can pause and
restart the emulation with these buttons. When it is paused it takes virtually
no CPU time.


You can pause and restart fMSX from the MSX screen by pressing the HELP key.


Music mode allows you to listen to music produced by the MSX without the
overhead of constant screen redraws. This mode makes fMSX a reasonably
effective music player.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Reset@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button resets the MSX. It is necessary to reset the MSX for some settings
to take effect.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}MSX version@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Selects what version of the MSX ROMs is used. The following choices are
available:


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} MSX1. These are the basic, original MSX ROMs. MSX2
games (or better) will not run with these ROMs.


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} MSX2. Required for MSX2 games, but also compatible
with all MSX1 games. You may still prefer to use MSX1 ROMs with MSX1 games
because of the superior boot time of the MSX1 ROMs.


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} MSX2+. Required for MSX2+ games. Currently almost
unsupported. Required if you want to use the second Kanji ROM bank.


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Coleco. Although not technically an MSX, a
Colecovision is close enough that selecting Coleco ROMs will turn fMSX into a
Colecovision system ;-)
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Cartridge 1@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If fMSX is configured to have a cartridge in slot 1, here is where you can
specify what cartridge you want. You have to specify the name of the
cartridge in the string gadget, and (only for cartridges bigger than 32K)
what type of cartridge it is.


The cartridge will be loaded and executed when you reset the MSX.


@{I}For cartridges bigger than 32K only:@{UI}


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} If the cartridge type is not set correctly the cartridge will
certainly not run!
If you do not know the correct setting for a cartridge you have
no option but to try them all. A list of known settings is
available @{"here" link games.guide/main}.


@{I}For cartridges of 32K or less:@{UI}


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The cartridge type does not have any effect.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Cartridge 2@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If fMSX is configured to have a cartridge in slot 2, you can specify its
parameters here. See @{B}Cartridge 1@{UB} for more information.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Diskdrives@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If fMSX is configured to use disks, a pane will be visible where you can enter
disk-related information. You can specify the number of disks used, the names
of the disks, and whether the disks are currently in use by the MSX or the
Amiga.


@{B}Drives@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

With this gadget you can specify the number of drives connected to the MSX.
Note that two drives need more MSX memory than one drive.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 Some games will not run if you have two drives connected due to memory shortage.


This setting only takes effect when you reset the MSX.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Lock drives@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

If this button has been checked the emulation can access the drive, but the
Amiga is locked out. Similarly, if it is not checked, the Amiga can access the
drive but the MSX cannot.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Drive A: and B:@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

In these gadgets you have to specify what is used as an MSX disk. You have
three options:


@{I}When you want to use real disks:@{UI}


You can use real disks with fMSX, or Amiga-devices that look like disks (such
as an appropriately formatted ramdisk). In order to be used with fMSX such a
device must meet certain criteria, which are:


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must have a blocksize of 512.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must have a low-cyl of 0.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must have a high-cyl of 39 or 79.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must have 9 blocks per track.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must be a real device. It cannot be an assign or volume.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} The device must be mounted.


The PC0: device that comes with OS3.x meets these criteria, and can be used
with fMSX.


To use a device, just type its name in one of the drive gadgets.


Example: "PC0:"


@{I}When you want to use a disk image:@{UI}


A disk image is a copy of a real disk, stored on your harddisk. Several types
are supported, including raw, .IMG, and .DDI. To use a disk image, type its
name in one of the drive gadgets.


Example: "hd2:msxdisks/PassengersOnTheWind.DDI"


@{I}When you want to use MSX files stored as files:@{UI}


fMSX Amiga can create a temporary, on the fly disk image from a directory that
contains MSX programs. Temporary disks created in this fashion are
always write protected (this means that the MSX can never write to your
harddisk directly). However, you can make a copy of the image after it was
created and use that as a normal (writeable) diskimage. Only one temporary
disk can be used at any one time (the second disk, if in use, must be a real
device or disk image).


To use a directory as a temporary disk image, again just type its name in one
of the drive gadgets.


Example: "hd2:msxdirs/A/Avenger/"
@{lindent 4}

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node CHEATWINDOW "The cheat window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The cheat window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

This window allows you to find cheats in games. This is done by finding the
address that stores the number of lives, ammo, etc., and modifying it.


To find the number of lives, start playing the game you want to cheat in. Put
the number of lives (or whatever you want to cheat) in the "value to search
for" gadget. Press the "search" button. A list of all addresses containing the
value you specified is put in the listview on the righthand side of the
window.


Now continue to play the game, until the value you want to modify changes (ie. you
loose a life or something). Put the new value in the "value to search for"
gadget. Again, press "search". All addresses in the address list are checked,
and are removed if they do not match the new value.


You can repeat this process as often as you want, until presumably you have
only one address left. At this point you can open a @{"memory editor" link MEMVIEWER} and change
the address to whatever value you like.


If you want to start a new search, make sure the "start new search"
radiobutton is pressed.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node MEMVIEWER "The memory editor"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The memory editor@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Although unfinished, the memory editor is already quite useful. In it you can
look at all pages of memory currently seen by the MSX. However, you can only
change those pages that represent RAM (ROM pages cannot be changed). The type
of page is listed at the bottom of the window.


At the left of the window you will find the address column. This shows the
address of the first byte shown on the same line. You can move the cursor into
the address column, and type a new address. This will cause you to be
teleported to that address.


The next set of columns show bytes of memory in hexadecimal representation,
and the rightmost column shows the same bytes in ASCII format. You can use
both columns to examine memory and change it.


You can open an unlimited number of memory editors.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node SYSPREFSWINDOW "The system preferences window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The system preferences window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

This window allows you to specify several system related settings for the
emulation.


@{B}Instruction threshold@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

On slower computers, MSX interrupts may happen too fast. In some programs this
can cause problems, because certain critical code that must be executed before
a new interrupt occurs has not yet completed.


With this slider you can set the minimum number of branch-type instructions
that MUST be executed before an interrupt is allowed. In normal code there are
about 4.7 normal instructions per branch-type instruction.


In interrupt driven games, setting this to a low number speeds the game up,
while high numbers slow it down. If the program you run does most of its work
outside the interrupt, setting it to a low number may actually slow things
down.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 If this number is set too low, it may crash the MSX. Try again
with a larger number. A value of 1500 should always be safe.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Maximum MSX speed@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This slider is used to precisely determine the speed of the MSX. It is only
available in the '060 version of fMSX.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}MSX configuration@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

@{B}Joystick 1 device@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

Allows you to use your mouse instead of a joystick for MSX joystick 1. Useful
for MSX programs that support a mouse. Examples of these are productivity
packages (such as Ease or Hybrid), but also games (such as l'Affaire,
Arkanoid, or Passengers on the Wind).


Usually the mouse detection is done at the start of the program, so be sure to
set this gadget correctly before you start anything.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Memory@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

With this gadget you can select the amount of memory the emulated MSX uses.
Note that the amount of free BASIC memory is constant (about 23KB), no matter
how big a number you put here. The biggest you will ever need is the 512KB
setting. The other settings are provided to let you boast about the amount of
memory your MSX can use ;-)
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Use Japanese ROM ID@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

When turned on, the country ID bytes in the ROM files are set to Japanese.
This causes some games to act differently. Examples:

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Nemesis 1 gets a new name (Gradius).

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Nemesis 2 uses Japanese text.

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Nemesis 3 gets an animated title screen.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Enable kanji ROM@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

When turned on, fMSX loads the kanji ROM into the system. This is a 256KB ROM
that contains definitions for 8192 kanji characters. Not many programs require
this ROM, and even then you need to be able to understand kanji before it is
of any use.


If you see 16x16 blocks of solid color in places where you would expect
characters, try enabling the kanji ROM.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Emulator configuration{UB}
@{lindent 4}

@{B}Save preferences on quit@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

When turned on, fMSX preferences are saved when the program ends. When turned
off it is necessary to save preferences by hand, using the menu option
Preferences/Save as... or Preferences/Save default.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Plug'n'Play@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

When turned on fMSX will reset automatically after you select a cartridge from
the filerequester or when you drop a cartridge on the fMSX window. This way
you get to play it even faster ;-)
@{lindent 4}


@{B}Autofire@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

When turned on, autofire is emulated for the joystick buttons (only for the
first button) and for the spacebar.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Slot configuration@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The MSX standard allows a number of memory configurations. In a normal MSX
this would be fixed, but fMSX allows you to choose several possible options.


The term 'slot' refers to both a physical cartridge slot and a logical memory
slot. A normal MSX has four slots, numbered 0..3.


Slot 0 is normally completely internal. In most machines (including fMSX) this
slot only contains the BASIC and BIOS ROMs.


Slots 1 and 2 are usually external, and can contain anything the user might
want to put in. In fMSX you can choose to put a game cartridge, disk interface
cartridge, or FM-Pac cartridge in either of these two slots. fMSX does not
support the use of two disk interfaces or two FM-Pacs, but two cartridges is
certainly possible, and there are a few games (mainly from Konami) that have
extra features if a specific second cartridge is present.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 Many games will detect the presence of the FM-Pac ROM, and will configure
themselves to produce only FM music (and no PSG music). Unless you select an
FM soundmode (either PSG+FM-Pac or Concierto FM-Pac) you will not hear any
music in those games.


Slot 3 is again internal, and usually contains RAM.


@{I}Expanded slots:@{UI}


fMSX also supports an MSX feature known as 'expanded slots'. This feature can
be enabled with the @{B}Expand slot 3@{UB} gadget. When enabled, the disk
interface and FM-Pac are hidden beneath the RAM banks in slot 3 (which means
that slots 1 and 2 are both available for cartridges). However...


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 Expanded slots are a real pain when it comes to compatibility. When expanded
slots are enabled, many games will not run.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 When slot 3 is expanded, fMSX will always load the FM-Pac ROM. As explained
above, this means you will not hear any PSG sound in many games.


If you wish to use expanded slots, the following BASIC command greatly
increases compatibility and should be used after every reset of your MSX:
@{fg shine}POKE -1,0@{fg text}.


Technical explanation: this command changes the default subslot number to 0,
which means that programs that do not understand subslots will get to see RAM
when switching the primary slot to slot 3. If you don't understand what that
means, it translates into "more games work".
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Compatibility@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This pane allows you to select special compatibility features that will be
needed only rarely, and that give a significant performance penalty when
selected.


Currently only one option is available.


@{B}Interrupt handler@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

There are two possibilities here: 'fast' and 'accurate'. In 99% of all cases,
fast will be your best choice. However, a few games (those that have been
hacked by SMA and start with their intro) rely on very specific interrupt
behavior. This behavior can be selected by setting Interrupt handler to
'accurate'.


If a game fails to start, try it with Interrupt handler set to
'accurate'. If it works it may be possible to switch back to 'fast' later on.
In all other cases you are better off in 'fast' mode.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node AUDIOWINDOW "The audio window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The audio window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

In this window you can select the many sound options supported by fMSX Amiga.
The six soundmodes are:


@{B}Off@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

In this mode fMSX does not produce any sound.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}PSG@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This is the Programmable Sound Generator, the standard MSX soundchip. The
sound is emulated through direct hardware access. 85% of all software only
uses PSG sound.


The PSG has three tone channels and one noise channel. The emulated PSG sounds
identical to the original.


The '060 version supports digitized MSX speech in this mode. The normal
version will also attempt to reproduce speech, but success depends on how
closely the speed of the emulated Z80 matches the speed of a real one.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}SCC@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This is the special soundchip used by Konami in some of their games. Instead
of blockwaves, like the PSG, the SCC uses 32-byte samples which sounds much
better. It has 5 channels, of which only 4 are emulated in this mode.


Only a few games support SCC. These games are:

@{code}
    @{U}MSX1 games@{UU}                @{U}MSX2 games@{UU}
    Salamander                Space Manbow
    Nemesis 2                 Metal Gear 2
    Nemesis 3                 Quarth
    King's Valley 2           Gryzor
    F1 Spirit                 King's Valley 2 MSX2
    Parodius                  The Snatcher (actually SCC+)
                              SD Snatcher (actually SCC+)
@{body}

In the pane marked "SCC options", you can select to @{B}emulate the SCC as an
SCC+@{UB} chip. The SCC+ is slightly different from the SCC (it allows five
waveforms instead of four, and is addressed on different addresses). Only the
two Snatcher games support SCC+ sound.


In the same pane, you can also select to emulate the @{B}channel disable
mode@{UB} of the SCC. This option compensates for a very strange (and very
hard to emulate) SCC feature. In F1-Spirit, the sound quality is notably
better when disable mode is off; in Parodius, it sounds better with disable
mode on; and for other games it doesn't appear to matter very much.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 SCC sound is only available if an SCC-capable cartridge is present in
one of the slots! This means that either slot 1 or slot 2 must be set to
'Cartridge', and the cartridge type for that cartridge must be set to either
'SCC 1' or 'SCC 2'.


The SCC emulation sounds very good, but in this mode a lot of channels are
missing.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}PSG + SCC@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

In this mode fMSX uses AHI to play all PSG and SCC channels simultaneously.
This is a bit slower than direct hardware access, but it sounds MUCH better,
allowing you to hear the (often spectacular) SCC songs the way they were
supposed to be heard. If you like Konami's musical style (and who doesn't?)
you should really install AHI and listen to the songs in this mode.


The same remarks about the SCC options apply here, and the sound quality is
spot on.


Digitized speech is not supported in this mode.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}PSG + FM-Pac@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The FM-Pac is an OPL/L soundchip, which was sold in a separate cartridge. The
FM-Pac supports 9 channels of FM sound, which is currently emulated at an
extremely basic level. Quite a few games support FM-Pac. FM-Pac emulation
requires AHI to be installed on your machine.


The FM-Pac will not work without its ROM. To use FM-sound, an FM-Pac ROM must
be present in one of the slots (see the @{"system preferences" LINK SYSPREFSWINDOW}).


Note that many games will detect the presence of the FM-Pac ROM and will
configure themselves for FM music only, ie. they will not produce any PSG
music when an FM-Pac ROM is present.


Unfortunately the software emulation doesn't sound very good. Digitized speech
is not supported in this mode.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Concierto FM-Pac@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

In this mode fMSX uses the Concierto soundcard (which is an add-on to the
Picasso IV graphics card) to emulate the FM-PAC. The emulation is very good;
not surprising, since the OPL3 used in the Concierto is a descendant of the
OPLL used in the FM-PAC. A Concierto soundcard is required to use this mode.


In this mode digitized speech (using the PSG) is also supported.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}AHI mode@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button lets you select the AHI mode fMSX uses. AHI is used in the
combined PSG/SCC soundmode, as well as the combined PSG/FM-Pac soundmode, and
the AHI mode determines the quality of the sound in that mode.


Selecting higher frequencies increases the quality of the sound. Unfortunately
higher frequencies require more CPU power as well, causing fMSX to run slower.
Experiment to find a good setting.


You should not select a stereo mode, as fMSX only generates mono sound.


If you don't have AHI installed this option is not available. AHI can be
obtained from Aminet.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node VIDEOPREFSWINDOW "The video settings window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The video settings window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

This window allows you to specify several video related settings for the
emulation.


@{B}The screen selector@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The listview at the top of the window shows the various screenmodes used by
fMSX Amiga. The program will always attempt to use the screenmode with the
smallest possible resolution and number of colors. Most programs will happily
run with just the 256*212, 16 colors mode.


You can change the display mode used in any resolution and color depth by
selecting that line in the listview, and pressing the @{B}select
screenmode@{UB} button. This will bring up an ASL requester which allows you
to choose a screenmode of your liking.


Currently, the 24-bit modes are unused by fMSX Amiga. They will be required in
a future version, when MSX2+ screens are also supported (MSX2+ can display up
to 19268 colors on a screen).


It is possible to substitute an Extra Half Brite mode for any of the 256 color
modes. fMSX Amiga will gracefully degrade to 64 colors.


Some of the modes presented in the listview are impossible on a real MSX, but
can still occur when the software is using a screensplit of some sort
(example: a 512*212 screen in 256 colors is impossible on a real MSX2, but the
top half of the screen could be in 512*212 in 16 colors, while the bottom half
is in 256*212 in 256 colors. fMSX Amiga doesn't deal well with this situation,
but it will attempt to make things look good).
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Go to current screenmode@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

With this button you can select the item in the listview that represents the
current screenmode. Useful for when you want to make a quick adjustment, but
do not know which screenmode is currently in use.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Select screenmode@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Pressing this button brings up the ASL screenmode requester for the screenmode
currently selected in the listview. You should choose a screenmode that fits
the MSX screenmode you selected in the listview for optimal viewing pleasure.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Only refresh when active@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

When this option is turned on and the MSX window is deselected, the emulator
will no longer redraw the MSX screen. This frees up some computing power when
you work in another application while fMSX is running.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Hide titlebar@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This turns the titlebar of the MSX screen on and off.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Run on public screen@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

fMSX can run on a public screen. You can specify a screenname, or you can
select the default public screen by leaving the stringgadget blank.

This option is only available when CyberGfx or Picasso'96 is installed. It
will not work on normal Amiga screens.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node TAPEPREFSWINDOW "The tape window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The tape window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

In this window you can control how fMSX deals with tape images. Tape images
are stored by fMSX Amiga as a collection of files, similar to the way a real
MSX stores files on tape. However, files on tape are ordered by nature, which
is not quite true for files on disk.


To emulate the ordering of files on a tape fMSX uses an index file. This is a
simple text file which lists all the files in the right order. The index file
should be in the same directory as the files it indexes.


@{B}Index@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The load button is used to load the index file of a tape. After selecting an
index file the contents of the tape are shown in the listview. It is also
possible to type in a pathname directly.


You can select a name that doesn't yet exist. If you do so, a new index will
be created.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Append@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The biggest problem with writing to a real tape is positioning it. No matter
how careful you are, the day will come when you accidentally overwrite
something important.


The 'append' option prevents this. When turned on, new files are always
appended to the end of a tape. When turned off, new files will overwrite the
currently selected file.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}The tape contents listview@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The listview shows the contents of the currently selected tape. The tape is
positioned just before the highlighted item. This means that the next item
loaded by the MSX (or saved, if 'Append' is turned off) will be the selected
item.


It is possible to change the name of an item. To do this, select it and type
the new name in the stringgadget at the bottom of the window. @{B}It is
strongly recommended that you do this for newly created files.@{UB} fMSX
searches for possible new filenames by simply going through a range of
filenames and trying them all. The more filenames exist in this range, the
longer the search takes.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Up@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button moves the currently selected file upwards in the index, ie.
forwards on tape.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Down@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button moves the currently selected file downwards in the index, ie.
backwards on tape.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Mark@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button marks the currently selected file for deletion. It will be
deleted when you press the 'Remove marked' button.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Clear@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

This button unmarks the currently selected file.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Remove marked@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The Remove button removes all marked files from tape. The files are removed
from both the index and your harddisk.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node MENUBAR "The menu bar"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The menu bar@{fg text}

@{jleft}

@{B}Project/About...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Brings up the 'about' requester.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Project/Quit@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Quits the program.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Cartridge/Save config. cartridge 1@{UB}

@{B}Cartridge/Save config. cartridge 2@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Saves several settings in the icon of the specified cartridge. If the
cartridge does not have an icon, the @{fg shine}fmsx_rom.info@{fg text} icon
(in the program directory) is used. If this icon does not exist either, no
information is saved.


You can also edit the @{"icon" link TOOLTYPES} manually.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Diskdrives/Write bootblock drive A:@{UB}

@{B}Diskdrives/Write bootblock drive B:@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The MSX cannot boot from disks that have a PC bootblock. With these menu
options you can write an MSX bootblock to one of the MSX drives.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 Some games have their own bootblocks. Overwriting them will kill the game.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Diskdrives/Create 360KB diskimage@{UB}

@{B}Diskdrives/Create 720KB diskimage@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

With these options you can create a new diskimage. Select the size you want,
pick a location and name in the filerequester, and it's ready for use. There
is no need to write a bootblock to a diskimage created in this manner.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Tools/Cheat finder...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Open the @{"cheat finder" link CHEATWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Tools/Memory editor...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Open a @{"memory editor" link MEMVIEWER} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Open...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens a previously saved fMSX settings file.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Save as...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

@{lindent 0}
Saves a settings file to a location of your choosing. You can reopen such
a file later by selecting the @{B}Settings/open@{UB} menu option.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Save default@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Saves fMSX settings. Settings are saved to the file @{fg shine}fmsx2.prefs@{fg text} in the
ENV: and ENVARC: directories.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Audio...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens the @{"audio settings" link AUDIOWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Paths...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens the @{"paths" link PATHSWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/System...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens the @{"system settings" link SYSPREFSWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Tape...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens the @{"tape settings" link TAPEPREFSWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Settings/Video...@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Opens the @{"video settings" LINK VIDEOPREFSWINDOW} window.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node TOOLTYPES "Icon tooltypes"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Icon tooltypes@{fg text}

@{jleft}

For both cartridges, diskimages, and directories with MSX files, the optimal
settings can be stored in an icon. The tooltypes of the icon are interpreted
as if they were ARexx commands, thus any command that can be executed from
ARexx is also valid as a tooltype!


For a complete list of commands, look @{"here" link arexx.guide/main}

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node PATHSWINDOW "The paths window"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}The paths window@{fg text}

@{jleft}

This window lets you specify paths to several external resources.


@{B}Enable external ROMs@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If turned on fMSX will load the MSX system ROM files from disk instead of
using the internal ones. You will need to specify what ROM files get loaded
using the appropriate string gadget. Note that internal ROMs are always used
when the external ROMs are not available.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}MSX1 rom, etc.@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

In this set of stringgadgets you can select which ROMs are used by fMSX in the
various modes. The ROM appropriate to the selected mode is used; if this ROM
cannot be found on disk the internal version will be used.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Enable external fonts@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

When activated an external MSX font is substituted for the internal ROM
font. If you can read Japanese, selecting the Japanese font makes many games
readable.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}MSX font@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Here you can select which font the MSX uses as its ROM font.

Many fonts are provided, including:

@{code}
@{U}Font@{UU}      @{U}Description@{UU}
Default   This is the same font that is present in the internal ROMs.
Italic    This is the same as the default font, but has italicized characters.
Japanese  This is a font containing Japanese characters.
Cyrillic  This is a font containing Cyrillic (Russian) characters.
@{body}

Note that the fonts are in MSX format, not in Amiga format. The two font
formats are not compatible with each other.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Temporary disk@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Since version 2.0, fMSX Amiga can create disks on the fly from directories. A
temporary disk image is created that contains all the files from the selected
directory. With this gadget you can select where the temporary disk image must
be created and what its name should be.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node DISK "Using MSX diskdrives"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Using MSX diskdrives@{fg text}

@{jleft}

The MSX disk system is an extension of the original MS-DOS disk system.
Anything you know about MS-DOS probably applies to MSX as well. This section
gives a short overview of features.


MSX filenames, like MS-DOS filenames, are very limited: they have a maximum
length of eight characters, followed by a three-character extension. In
addition, no lower-case characters or spaces are allowed.


The number of files on a disk is limited to 112. To make matters worse,
subdirectories are not supported by MSX.


There are two wildcards: @{fg shine}*@{fg text} and @{fg shine}?@{fg text}.
These correspond to the Amiga wildcards @{fg shine}#?@{fg text} and @{fg shine}?@{fg text}.


@{U}example@{UU}    @{U}means@{UU}

@{fg shine}*.*@{fg text}        Everything

@{fg shine}*.BAS@{fg text}      All files with extension @{fg shine}.BAS@{fg text}

@{fg shine}GAME*.*@{fg text}    All files starting with @{fg shine}GAME@{fg text}

@{fg shine}*.B??@{fg text}      All files that have a @{fg shine}B@{fg text} as the first part of the extension.


fMSX Amiga supports up to two diskdrives. The MSX calls these drives @{fg shine}
A:@{fg text} and @{fg shine}B:@{fg text}.


There are two ways of dealing with disks on the MSX: by using
@{"MSX-DOS" link MSXDOS} and from @{"BASIC" link DISKBASIC}.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node MSXDOS "About MSX-DOS"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}About MSX-DOS@{fg text}

@{jleft}

MSX-DOS is a control program for the MSX which is based on the very first
version of MS-DOS. It is required if you want to use some MSX programs, and it
can be useful if you want to perform certain floppy operations. It is close
enough to CP/M that some CP/M programs run on it; many others only require
minor modifications to run.


MSX programs that require MSX-DOS can easily be recognized by their filename.
Programs that end in @{fg shine}.BAT@{fg text} are MSX-DOS script files;
programs that end in @{fg shine}.COM@{fg text} are MSX-DOS executables. Both
types can be started by typing the filename (without the extension) after the
prompt.


@{B}Getting started@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

To run MSX-DOS you need three things: an MSX-formatted floppy, and the
programs @{fg shine}MSXDOS.SYS@{fg text} and @{fg shine}COMMAND.COM@{fg text}.
Obtaining an MSX-formatted floppy is easy: any 720KB PC floppy will do.


Step 1: Find, buy, or format a PC floppy. Assuming you have CrossDos installed
this can easily be done from your workbench.


Step 2: Make sure that fMSX is configured with a disk interface. This can be
done in the @{"system preferences" link SYSPREFSWINDOW} window.


Step 3: In the main window, check that the Drives button is set to 1 or 2. If
it isn't, change the setting and reset fMSX by clicking the @{B}Reset@{UB}
button in the control window.


Step 4: Convert the disk to MSX format by selecting the menu option @{B}Write
bootblock@{UB} (for the appropriate device).


Step 5: Copy @{fg shine}MSXDOS.SYS@{fg text} and @{fg shine}
COMMAND.COM@{fg text} to this floppy.


Step 6: Reset fMSX by clicking the Reset button.


Step 7: Wait until MSX-DOS has booted. One of the first things you'll see is
the prompt, which looks like this: @{fg shine}A>@{fg text}


When MSX-DOS boots it looks for a file called @{fg shine}AUTOEXEC.BAT@{fg text}.
This is a script file that is executed automatically if found.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Complete overview of commands@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Each command is followed by one or more examples. The lines between square
brackets represent BASIC equivalents for the MSX-DOS examples.


@{U}BASIC@{UU}

Quits MSX-DOS and returns you to the BASIC interpreter. From there you can
type CALL SYSTEM or _SYSTEM to go back to MSX-DOS. Note: this doesn't work if
you didn't originally boot from an MSX-DOS disk.


Examples:

A>BASIC         (starts BASIC)

[CALL SYSTEM] or [_SYSTEM]

A>BASIC start.bas   (starts BASIC and runs the BASIC program start.bas)

[no equivalent]


@{U}COPY@{UU}

Copies one or more files.


Examples:

A>COPY A:*.* B:     (copies all files from drive A: to drive B:)

[COPY "A:*.*" TO "B:"]

A>COPY MSX.TXT PRN  (copies the file msg.txt to the printer)

[COPY "MSX.TXT" TO "PRN"]


@{U}DATE@{UU}

Shows the date. Optionally you can also change it.


Examples:

A>DATE          (shows the current date)

[GETDATE A$ : PRINT A$] (requires MSX2 BASIC)


@{U}DEL@{UU}

Removes a file from disk.


Examples:

A>DEL *.*       (removes all files)

[KILL "*.*"]


@{U}DIR@{UU}

Shows the contents of a disk.


Examples:

A>DIR *.BAS     (shows all files with extension .BAS)

[FILES "*.BAS"]

A>DIR /P        (shows all files, pausing after every page of output)

[no equivalent]

A>DIR /W        (shows all files in shortened format)

[FILES]


@{U}ERASE@{UU}

Same as DEL.


@{U}FORMAT@{UU}

Allows you to format a disk. Not supported by fMSX Amiga, you'll have to
format a disk from the workbench instead. Don't forget to write an MSX
bootblock to it.


@{U}MODE@{UU}

Change the width of the screen.


Examples:

A>MODE 40       (turns on 40-column mode)

[WIDTH 40]


@{U}PAUSE@{UU}

Puts the text @{fg shine}Strike any key when ready...@{fg text} on the screen and waits until
any key has been struck. It can also print an extra message.


Examples:

A>PAUSE         (waits until a key has been struck)

[no equivalent]

A>PAUSE Message     (prints Message on screen and waits)

[no equivalent]


@{U}REM@{UU}

Does nothing at all. If any text follows the REM statement it is printed on
screen.


Examples:

A>REM Message       (prints Message)

[no equivalent]


@{U}REN@{UU}

Renames one or more files.


Examples:

A>REN *.LDR *.BAS   (changes all .LDR extensions to .BAS extensions)

[NAME "*.LDR" AS "*.BAS"]


@{U}RENAME@{UU}

Same as REN.


@{U}TIME@{UU}

Shows the time. Optionally you can also change it.


Examples:

A>TIME          (shows the current time)

[GETTIME A$ : PRINT A$] (requires MSX2 BASIC)


@{U}TYPE@{UU}

Prints the contents of a file on the screen.


Examples:

A>TYPE MSG.TXT      (shows the contents of MSG.TXT)

[COPY "MSG.TXT" TO "CON"]


@{U}VERIFY@{UU}

Turns on verification mode. This command is actually ignored by MSX.


Examples:

A>VERIFY ON     (turns verification on)

[no equivalent]

A>VERIFY OFF        (turns verification off)

[no equivalent]

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node DISKBASIC "Using the drives from BASIC"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Using the drives from BASIC@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Unlike MSX-DOS, BASIC enforces no filenaming conventions for executables or
other kinds of files. However, some guidelines exist:


@{B}BASIC files:@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Files ending in @{fg shine}.BAS@{fg text} are BASIC files. There are several
ways to load them:


LOAD "FILENAME.BAS"     (loads the file)

LOAD "FILENAME.BAS",R   (loads the file and executes it)

RUN "FILENAME.BAS"      (loads the file and executes it)


If you want to save a BASIC file you can use this:


SAVE "FILENAME.BAS"
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Executables:@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Files ending in @{fg shine}.BIN@{fg text} are executable files. There is only
one way to load them:


BLOAD "FILENAME.BIN",R  (loads the file and executes it)
@{lindent 0}


@{B}MSX-DOS files:@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Files ending in @{fg shine}.BAT@{fg text} or @{fg shine}.COM@{fg text} are
files that can only be used from @{"MSX-DOS" link MSXDOS}.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Other files:@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If the file you want to load has another kind of extension, try experimenting
with it. The MSX will tell you if you did something wrong.


There is one file that has special significance to MSX-BASIC. This file is
called @{fg shine}AUTOEXEC.BAS@{fg text} and is executed automatically during
the boot sequence.


The section about @{"MSX-DOS" link MSXDOS} contains BASIC equivalents for some
MSX-DOS statements.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node QUITTING "Quitting the emulator"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Quitting the emulator@{fg text}

@{jleft}

There are three ways to quit the emulator: select @{B}Quit@{UB} from the menu,
close the control window, or send an ARexx quit command to the ARexx port.


If the option 'Save preferences' is activated, quitting the emulator also
causes it to write many current settings to disk. These values are
automatically reloaded the next time you run the program.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node CONFIGURE "Configuring your MSX"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Configuring your MSX@{fg text}

@{jleft}

A real MSX2 has a small amount of battery-backed RAM, which is used to store
(among other things) information about your preferred working environment.


The following commands are used to customize the environment:


@{B}SCREEN n@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Sets the desired screenmode. n can be 0 or 1.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}WIDTH n@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Selects the amount of columns of text displayed on screen. Valid values for
n are 80 or less for screen 0, and 32 or less for screen 1.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}COLOR fore,back,border@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Selects foreground, background, and border colors. Screen 0 does not support
border colors; one of the many weird features of the MSX2 VDP. Colors range
from 0 to 15.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}KEY [ON|OFF]@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Turns the function key list underneath the screen on or off.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}SET PROMPT "prompt"@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Changes the prompt to "prompt". The maximum length of the prompt is six
characters. Tip: if you often use the "Files" command (like me), it may be
useful to set it as the prompt.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}SET SCREEN@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Stores the current settings in battery backed RAM. fMSX actually keeps a copy
of these values on disk, in the file @{fg shine}fmsx2.prefs@{fg text}.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node AMIGAHARDWARE "Using the Amiga hardware"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Using the Amiga hardware@{fg text}

@{jleft}


@{B}Keyboard@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Depending on whether fMSX is in MSX or Colecovision mode, you get a slightly
different keyboard layout. However, the following keys work in both modes:

@{code}
@{U}Amiga key@{UU}   @{U}Function@{UU}
help        Pause fMSX
numeric (   Use Amiga mouseport for the second joystick
@{body}

@{I}For MSX:@{UI}


Keys are directly mapped to their MSX equivalents, which means that the MSX
ROMs determine what character results from a key press. The ROMs that come
with this version of fMSX Amiga give you an American keymap.


Some keys that may not be obvious:

@{code}
@{U}Amiga key@{UU}   @{U}MSX key@{UU}
F6          @{fg shine}select@{fg text}
F7          @{fg shine}stop@{fg text}
F8          @{fg shine}clear/home@{fg text}
F9          @{fg shine}insert@{fg text}
F10/delete  @{fg shine}delete@{fg text}
left alt    @{fg shine}graphics@{fg text}
right alt   @{fg shine}code@{fg text}
numeric )   @{fg shine},@{fg text}
@{body}

The Amiga keys and the extra international keys found on some keyboards are
not used by fMSX.


@{I}For Colecovision:@{UI}


The two numerical pads of the Colecovision are emulated on the Amiga keyboard,
and the joysticks are emulated as Amiga joysticks.

@{code}
@{U}Player 1 key@{UU}    @{U}Player 2 key@{UU}   @{U}Coleco Key@{UU}
numeric 0       0              @{fg shine}0@{fg text}
numeric 1       1              @{fg shine}1@{fg text}
numeric 2       2              @{fg shine}2@{fg text}
numeric 3       3              @{fg shine}3@{fg text}
numeric 4       4              @{fg shine}4@{fg text}
numeric 5       5              @{fg shine}5@{fg text}
numeric 6       6              @{fg shine}6@{fg text}
numeric 7       7              @{fg shine}7@{fg text}
numeric 8       8              @{fg shine}8@{fg text}
numeric 9       9              @{fg shine}9@{fg text}
numeric -       -              @{fg shine}?@{fg text}
numeric +       =              @{fg shine}?@{fg text}
right shift     left shift     @{fg shine}?@{fg text}
@{body}

If anyone knows what those question mark keys are on the Colecovision joypad,
please tell me!
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Joystick@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The emulator can use two Amiga joysticks. The second joystick is activated by
pressing '(' on the numeric keypad while in the emulation screen. Press '('
again to get the mouse back.


Joysticks with two buttons are very common with MSX systems, and many games
take advantage of the second button. Often there is a keyboard equivalent for
the second button; Konami games use 'M' and 'N' for this.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Video@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

The emulator should run fine on any Amiga screen, including PAL, NTSC,
CyberGfx, and Picasso'96.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Audio@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Depending on which soundmode is selected, fMSX will either use the Amiga
sound hardware directly or use AHI. AHI is available on Aminet.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}The Concierto soundcard@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If a Concierto soundcard is installed, fMSX can use it to emulate the FM-Pac.
FM-Pac emulation is spot-on using this card. No wonder; the OPL3 chip in the
Concierto is a descendant of the OPLL chip in the FM-Pac.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Clock@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

MSX2 machines have a built-in battery-backed clock. The emulator substitutes
the Amiga clock for this clock.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Diskdrives@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

MSX disk drives are emulated as Amiga devices. Read the section about
@{"diskdrives" link DISK} for more information.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Mouse@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Some MSX2 programs can use a mouse. Activate the mouse in the system
preferences window, and it will be available for use in those programs.


Normally it is turned off because an active mouse tends to confuse software
that is expecting a joystick.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node FUTURE "Future plans"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Future plans@{fg text}

@{jleft}
@{lindent 4}

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Complete printer support

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Support for MSX2+ and MSX Turbo-R

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Support for horizontal panning

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Snapshots

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Optional checks for sprite overrun or collision

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} A 'database' for cartridge and / or disk settings
(so no icons are necessary to play programs directly from CD)

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Emulation of MSX networking, including a version
that works over the internet ;-)

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Serial port emulation

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Improved FM-Pac support for AHI

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} A revolutionary GUI that will be completely
user-definable (it is currently in the design stage, I don't know whether it
will ever appear)

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Volume controls

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Better comparable volume (FM-Pac is relatively
loud now)

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Gadgethelp

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} HTML documentation

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Better memory viewer


... and of course as always

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Better compatibility

@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Higher speed

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node SOFTWARE "Where do I find MSX software?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Where do I find MSX software?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

MSX software is available through FTP from the following sites:
@{lindent 4}

@{code}
@{U}Site:@{UU}             @{U}Directory:@{UU}
ftp.funet.fi      /pub/msx/
komkon.com        /pub/MSX/
jazz.snu.ac.kr    /pub/msx
@{body}

MSX software is also available via WWW:

@{code}
@{U}Site:@{UU}
http://surf.to/fmsx
http://www.casema.net/~tfh/
http://www.cs.umd.edu/users/fms/
http://www.upcnet.upc.es/~jsp4/msx.html
http://dynamo.geol.msu.ru/msx/
http://home.earthlink.net/~tbelmont/msx/index.html
@{body}

... and many others!

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node ICONS "Why are the icons so ugly?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Why are the icons so ugly?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

There are two possible reasons.


The first is that your Workbench palette is different from mine. If you want
to see what the icons should look like, set your Workbench to 8 colors, and
use the following palette:


color #0-3: standard Commodore colors

color #4:   full red

color #5:   (unused)

color #6:   full blue

color #7:   (unused)


The second reason is that I am not an artist. Feel free to draw nicer icons,
if you like. And send me a copy!


A new set of icons was donated by Johan Forsberg (d92-jfo@nada.kth.se). These
icons use the Magic Workbench colors and are much better than my own poor
attempt at art.


A second set was donated by Halil Ibrahim Tasova (CaptainHIT@Gmx.net). These
are in glow icon format.


Thanks to both of you!

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node HOWTOLOAD "I don't understand how I'm supposed to load program <xxx>..."
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}I don't understand how I'm supposed to load program <xxx>...@{fg text}

@{jleft}

@{B}Diskbased software@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

An MSX filename consists of eight characters, followed by a dot and another
three characters. The last three characters are called the extension. The
extension generally tells you how to load a file. So, if the filename is...


@{U}xxx.BAT@{UU} or @{U}xxx.COM@{UU}

Go to @{"MSX-DOS" link MSXDOS} and type @{fg shine}xxx@{fg text}.


@{U}xxx.BAS@{UU}

Try the following: in BASIC, type @{fg shine}RUN "xxx.BAS"@{fg text}. If it
responds with an error message it isn't a BASIC file, try loading it as an
executable file.


@{U}xxx.BIN@{UU}

Try the following: in BASIC, type @{fg shine}BLOAD "xxx.BIN",R@{fg text}. If
it responds with an error message it isn't an executable file, try loading it
as a BASIC file.


@{U}xxx.PMA@{UU}

This is an MSX archive file, similar to a .LHA file on the Amiga. You need
PMEXT.COM (available from several @{"FTP sites" link SOFTWARE}) to unpack it.
PMEXT.COM requires @{"MSX-DOS" link MSXDOS}.


@{U}xxx.DSK@{UU}

@{U}xxx.DDI@{UU}

@{U}xxx.IMG@{UU}

These are disk images. See below for more information.


@{U}any other@{UU}

Try loading it as either a BASIC file or an executable file.


If none of these work, it is a file that is part of another program,
in which case it can only be loaded by that program.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Tapebased software@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Tapebased software consists of a group files and an index file (see the
description @{"here" link TAPEPREFSWINDOW}.


There are three ways to load files from tape:


@{fg shine}BLOAD "CAS:",R@{fg text}


This command loads the first binary file it can find from tape and executes it.


@{fg shine}LOAD "CAS:",R@{fg text}

@{fg shine}CLOAD@{fg text}


These commands load the first BASIC file they can find from tape. The MSX has
two ways to store BASIC files on tape, and they are not compatible. You must
use the right command for each type of file.

After loading a file with @{fg shine}CLOAD@{fg text} you must type @{fg
shine}RUN@{fg text} to activate it.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}ROM files and disk images must be loaded from the Amiga side@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Only MSX files can be loaded using MSX commands. ROM files and disk images are
not really MSX files (a real MSX cannot load them) and can only be loaded from
the Amiga side.


To load and activate ROM files you must use the @{B}Cartridge@{UB} and
@{B}Reset@{UB} buttons in the @{"control window" link CONTROLWINDOW}.


To load a diskimage or directory, use the @{B}Drive A:@{UB} or @{B}Drive
B:@{UB} buttons, also in the @{"control window" link CONTROLWINDOW}.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node COMPATIBILITY "Program <xxx> does not work, what can I do?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Program <xxx> does not work, what can I do?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Note: many tricks described here require you to reset fMSX before they take
effect.

There is an ARexx script in the ARexx drawer that sets fMSX to its most
compatible settings, as advised here. The script is called @{fg shine}
MostCompatible.fmsx@{fg text}.


@{B}Try a higher instruction threshold@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Some games perform lots of processing between every two interrupts, and the
emulated Z80 may not be able to keep up (this is especially true for
graphically intensive operations). If interrupts happen too early this may
cause the MSX to crash or behave erratically.


Setting the instruction threshold to a higher value causes the emulated Z80 to
perform at least a certain number of instructions between two interrupts. This
means that the game will run slower, but there is also a better chance of it
working at all.


A good example of a game that needs a higher interrupt period is Maze of
Galious.


The amount of instructions executed cannot easily be determined, but is
normally about five times higher than the instruction threshold.


Although it is possible to enter values as high as 5000 it is not normally
necessary to go above 1500. Note that you do not need to reboot for this
setting to take effect.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Use less drives@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Every drive costs a bit of BASIC memory. Many games will not run when more
than one drive is present, because the BASIC loader can run out of memory.
Turning off the second drive (using the appropriate gadget in the main window)
may help. Allocating more memory to the MSX will not help, this does not
increase BASIC memory at all. Such are the wonders of the MSX memory
architecture...


Tape-based software often fails to run completely when even a single drive is
present.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Use more memory@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Some games require an MSX device called a memory mapper to be installed. 98%
of all programs will feel at home on a 256Kb mapper, and the rest will run
fine with 512Kb. The amount of memory used by the memory mapper can be
selected in the @{"system preferences" link SYSPREFSWINDOW} window.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Use MSX1 ROMs@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Some MSX1 games do not properly turn off MSX2 features, causing garbage to
appear on the screen. Disable MSX2 in the system preferences window and see if
the problem disappears.


Of course MSX2 games will only work with MSX2 ROMs.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Use a different interrupt handler@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

fMSX has two different interrupt handlers, one that is fast and works fine in
99% of all cases, and one that is more accurate but a lot slower. Try using
the accurate interrupt handler if a game doesn't work with the fast handler.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Use a different cartridge type@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Cartridges bigger than 32K must have a correctly set cartridge type. If the
cartridge type is not set correctly, the cartridge will certainly not run.
Programs other than cartridges bigger than 32K are not affected by the
cartridge type.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Don't use expanded slots@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

Expanded slots cause many compatibility problems. Turning this feature off
will help a great deal. Alternatively, it can be turned off in BASIC by typing
@{fg shine}POKE -1,0@{fg text}.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Try hacking with BASIC@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

If all this doesn't help there is still a whole bag of BASIC tricks left to
try. Some of the following might do it; then again, it might not:


@{B}POKE -1,0@{UB} or @{B}POKE &hFFFF,0@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

These two commands are actually identical, and only help when subslot support
is turned on. However, for that situation it tends to help a great deal (using
this poke unlocks 70% or so of all software!).
@{lindent 4}


@{B}POKE &hFD9F,201@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

This turns off disk interrupt processing. On a real MSX this means the drive
engine never stops (this is regulated through this interrupt) but fMSX
controls the drive engine on its own.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}CLEAR 0@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

This frees up extra BASIC memory.
@{lindent 4}


@{B}MAXFILES = 0@{UB}
@{lindent 8}

This frees up extra BASIC memory.
@{lindent 0}


@{B}Get the next release@{UB}
@{lindent 4}

fMSX Amiga is still under development. I try to have better compatibility with
each new release. If something doesn't work send me a report and I'll see what
I can do.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node SNAPSHOTS "Will you ever implement snapshots?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Will you ever implement snapshots?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Since many other features have now been realized, I have been thinking about
this again lately. I may give it a try in a later version.


However, it won't be easy. The MSX does not have a flat memory space, but
consists of many different blocks of RAM, ROM, videoRAM and countless
customchip settings. Saving all of these would require a format that is highly
future proof, and preferably portable to other platforms. Designing such a
format is a difficult and time consuming job.


The real problem is not in saving though: when fMSX is running it constantly
builds up internal state information. Most information is kept twice: once in
MSX format, and once in pre-translated Amiga format. Reloading a snapshot
would require a complete translation of all loaded MSX data into Amiga data,
something which is very hard to do correctly.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node V060 "What is the difference between the normal and '060 versions?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}What is the difference between the normal and '060 versions?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

The normal version runs at the maximum possible speed. On the 68060 this is
usually much too fast, which makes some games unplayable.


The '060 version has special delay-code built in, which causes it to run at
exactly the same speed as a real Z80. This code in itself slows fMSX down
quite a lot!


In addition, the '060 version synchronizes the VDP (MSX blitter) and Z80. This
means that VDP commando's take as long in fMSX as they would take in a real
MSX. In some games this actually speeds things up.


@{bg highlight}! Warning !@{bg background}
 In most cases the 68060 version is a lot slower than the normal version.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node PPC "Will you implement a PPC version?"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}Will you implement a PPC version?@{fg text}

@{jleft}

I don't know yet. If I do, it will be a lot of work. Certainly all of the Z80
would have to be rewritten, as well as all the graphics routines.


Even then it may be slower than the current version. This depends heavily on
how much IO is really going on, ie. how often the program needs to switch back
to 680x0 mode.


For now, don't hold your breath.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node NEWVERSIONS "How to obtain new versions"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}How to obtain new versions@{fg text}

@{jleft}

New versions of fMSX Amiga will be distributed on Aminet, and I also mail a
copy to everybody on the fMSX Amiga distribution list. If you want to be
placed on this list (or removed from it) simply send mail to
@{fg shine}hguijt@inter.nl.net@{fg text} stating what you want. If you asked
to be on the list but aren't, try mailing me again. I am not a mail-demon, and
I occasionally misplace mail messages.


You do not need to fear being swamped by mail; there is usually a few months
between each successive version of the emulator.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node CSMSX "About comp.sys.msx"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}About comp.sys.msx@{fg text}

@{jleft}

For public questions about MSX or fMSX, your best bet would be the newsgroup
@{fg shine}comp.sys.msx@{fg text}. MSX users tend to be far more tolerant
about emulation than Amiga users.


I'm no longer on @{fg shine}comp.emulations.misc@{fg text}. There is just too
much noise in that group.


Of course, questions can be aimed at the @{"author" link AUTHOR} as well.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node AUTHOR "About the author"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}About the author@{fg text}

@{jleft}

fMSX Amiga is being written by Hans Guijt. I studied Computer Science at the
University of Leiden from 1989 to 1995. After that I found a job with Palm
Automatisering in Aalsmeer, where I programmed administrative software for the
flower trade. In 1997 I changed jobs again, this time to Terma Elektronik A/S,
a Danish company who have hired me out to the European Space Agency. Today I
still work for ESA at their ESTEC site, where I am responsible for designing
and building the STAMP system.


Larger past and present projects include:


@{I}During my studies:@{UI}


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} Photobase: a large UNIX based system for image
normalization and recognition, written for the University of Leiden. It can
load an image, and perform various normalizations on it. This process leads to
an image that isn't very pretty anymore, but can easily be correlated with
other images in a database. This allows pretty accurate image recognition.


@{I}During my time at Palm Automatisering:@{UI}


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} HuKra: a big administrative package for the flower
trade, written in PowerBuilder, on top of an Oracle database.


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} OZ: a data analysis package for the flower trade,
also written in PowerBuilder / Oracle.


@{I}Currently (at ESA):@{UI}


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} TempDAS/LMA: a small tool for controlling and
configuring the TempDAS measurement device, and presenting its output in a
fairly user-friendly fashion. Written in C++. Although of immense value during
the qualification stage of the TempDAS hardware, the software became mostly
obsolete upon completion of STAMP.


@{fg highlight}»»@{fg text} STAMP: a huge system for thermal measurement and
presentation, also written in C++. Its purpose is to gather data during space
craft test campaigns (that is the testing that is done on satellites and
pieces of the International Space Station before they are launched), present
this data in a variety of ways, and to control various pieces of equipment
related to the test facility.


Currently the STAMP system consists of some 20 distinct processes, running on
a network that consists of two HP-9000 servers (running HP-UX 10.20 in
parallel server configuration) and some 20 PCs (running W<mumble> '95 - yes, I
know...).


At the time of writing, the first phase of STAMP has been succesfully
completed. The code has passed the acceptance test, and has just been used in
the first real-life test campaign. The conclusion: software @{B}can@{UB} be
correct in its first release! ;-)


It took a long time to get to this point, and there were some bumps on the
road, but in the end STAMP has become a marvelous tool that doesn't just meet
expectations, but in fact exceeds them all over the board. I made many long
days (especially since the new year), but I am very proud of the end result!


My (snailmail) address:

@{code}
    Hans Guijt
    Frans Halslaan 193
    2343 EE Oegstgeest
    The Netherlands

    Telephone: (Holland) 715726602
    Email: hguijt@inter.nl.net
@{body}

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node RAMSX "About RAMSX:"
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}About RAMSX:@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Included in this package is a mountlist for a device called RAMSX:. This
device (built from ramdrive.device and crossdosfilesystem) can be used with
fMSX to play disk-based games directly from RAM.


RAMSX: has been largely obsoleted by the on-the-fly diskimage generation
feature of fMSX.


If you want to use RAMSX: you will need about 720Kb of free RAM and the
crossdosfilesystem. You must also enter the device name RAMSX: into the
appropriate drive gadget in the preferences window.


It can be rather hard to recover RAMSX after a reboot, but it can be done.
Open a shell and type the following commands:


    @{fg shine}assign RAMSX: dismount@{fg text}

    @{fg shine}mount RAMSX:@{fg text}


and RAMSX: is back online. Thanks to Nikos Drogosis (ndrog@acropolis.net) for
reporting this.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

@node FMSX0 ""
@smartwrap
@{jcenter}
@{fg highlight}About FMSX0: and FMSX1:@{fg text}

@{jleft}

Included in this package are mountlists for two devices called FMSX0: and
FMSX1:. These devices require fmsdisk.device to be installed. fmsdisk.device
is available from Aminet (directory misc/disk).


FMSX0: and FMSX1: allow you to store MSX disks on the Amiga harddisk. If you
wish to easily access floppy-based MSX disks but cannot be bothered with real
floppies these devices are an excellent alternative.


FMSX0: and FMSX1: have been largely obsoleted by the ability of fMSX to access
a disk image directly. Today they are mostly useful to access disk images
using Amiga disk tools.


The devices were contributed by Andrew G. Robson
(a.g.robson@northumbria.ac.uk). Complaints and compliments are rightly his.

@endnode

*****************************************************************

